 presumably as an Americanized form of some similar (like-sounding) Jewish surname."],"variants":[{"name":"Robert","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Marcel, Gilles, Normand, Armand, Lucien, Pierre, Emile, Michel, Edouard, Gaston, Yves.","French, Walloon, English, German, Dutch, Flemish, and Breton (of French origin); Hungarian (<b>Róbert</b>): from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Ro(d)bert</i> (Middle English <i>Robert</i>, Old French <i>Ro(d)bert</i>), composed of the elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame, renown’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This is found occasionally in Anglo-Saxon England before the Conquest, but in the main it was introduced into England by the Normans and quickly became popular among all classes of society. Pet forms and diminutives are found from an early date,   Robin   being particularly common. Compare   Robair  ,   Robar  ,   Robare  , and   Rober  .","In some cases also an Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish surnames."]},{"name":"Robers","meanings":["English: variant of   Roberts  ."]},{"name":"Roberds","meanings":["English: variant of   Roberts  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Robards","meanings":["English (Kent): variant of   Roberts  ."]},{"name":"Robarts","meanings":["English (Bedfordshire and Hertfortshire): variant of   Roberts  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Rookhurst Alias Roberts Of Rookhurst was born in 1254, in Scotland, United Kingdom as the son of Of Goodhurst William Rookhurst Alias Roberts. He married Margaret de la Zouch in 1274, in Kent, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"1254–":"1254–Surnud","1254–Male":"1254–Surnud","1254–Female":"1254–Surnud","1274–Male":"1274–Surnud","1230–Male":"1230–Surnud","Abt 1274":"umbes 1274","1254":"1254","1274":"1274","1230":"1230","Rookhurst, Kent, England":"Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Kent, England":"Kent, England"},"fi":{"1254–":"1254–Kuollut","1254–Male":"1254–Kuollut","1254–Female":"1254–Kuollut","1274–Male":"1274–Kuollut","1230–Male":"1230–Kuollut","Abt 1274":"noin 1274","1254":"1254","1274":"1274","1230":"1230","Rookhurst, Kent, England":"Kent, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Kent, England":"Kent, England"},"fr":{"1254–":"1254–Décédé","1254–Male":"1254–Décédé","1254–Female":"1254–Décédée","1274–Male":"1274–Décédé","1230–Male":"1230–Décédé","Abt 1274":"environ 1274","1254":"1254","1274":"1274","1230":"1230","Rookhurst, Kent, England":"Kent, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Écosse, Royaume-Uni","Kent, England":"Kent, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Robert Rookhurst Alias Roberts Of Rookhurst est né en 1254, à Écosse, Royaume-Uni, fils de Of Goodhurst William Rookhurst Alias Roberts. Il a épousé Margaret de la Zouch en 1274, à Kent, Angleterre. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fils."},"de":{"1254–":"1254–Verstorben","1254–Male":"1254–Verstorb